reference_summary: The table "HP LaserJet 4000 series - Comparison" provides a detailed comparison between the HP LaserJet 4200 and 4250 models within the HP LaserJet 4000 series. However, notable differences exist between the two models. The LaserJet 4200 features a 300 MHz CPU speed, while the 4250 boasts a faster 460 MHz CPU. Additionally, the 4200 model has a print speed of 35 PPM, slightly slower than the 4250's 43 PPM. The evolution of memory capacity within the HP LaserJet 4000 series is evident, with each subsequent model offering increased memory capabilities for enhanced performance. Starting from a maximum memory of 100 MB in the LaserJet 4000, the series progressed to 192 MB in the 4050 model, further increasing to 256 MB in the 4100 model, and eventually reaching a substantial 512 MB capacity in both the 4240 and 4250 models. Subsequent models like the 4300 and 4350 maintained the same maximum memory capacity as the 4240 and 4250 models, indicating a peak level of memory capacity achieved in the series. This progression highlights the continuous improvement in performance and functionality across different models within the HP LaserJet 4000 series.

table.title: Rio Grande class K-36 - Roster

reference_summary: The table "Rio Grande class K-36 - Roster" provides a detailed account of the historical trajectory and current status of various locomotives within this class. Locomotive 485 met a tragic end due to a crash in Salida, leading to its scrapping in 1955. In contrast, locomotive 483 transitioned to the Cumbres and Toltec Scenic Railroad in 1970, with a notable service milestone of hauling the last scheduled passenger train on the Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad in 1965. Locomotive 486, retired in 1962, found its way to the Durango and Silverton Narrow Gauge Railroad in 1999, where it currently resides. The D&SNG currently possesses four K-36 locomotives, with numbers 480, 481, and 486 reported as operational. However, the operational status of locomotive 482 remains uncertain following its retirement in 1962 and subsequent trade to D&SNG in 1991. This roster encapsulates the diverse fates and journeys of these iconic locomotives, reflecting the rich history and preservation efforts within the realm of railway heritage.
